5f.title: Preference framework
5f.clickbait: What's the thing an agent uses to compare its preferences?
5f.text:
[summary:  A 'preference framework' is a way of deciding which outcomes an agent [1bh terminally] prefers.  'Preference framework' is a broader term than '[1fw utility function]', since 'preference framework' would also include structurally complicated [meta_utility meta-utility] functions, such as those which appear in some proposals for [1b7] or [7s2].]

A 'preference framework' refers to a fixed algorithm that updates, or potentially changes in other ways, to determine what the agent [ prefers] for [1bh terminal] outcomes.  'Preference framework' is a term more general than '[1fw utility function]' which includes structurally complicated generalizations of utility functions.

As a central example, the [1b7 utility indifference] proposal has the agent switching between utility functions $U_X$ and $U_Y$ depending on whether a switch is pressed.  We can call this meta-system a 'preference framework' to avoid presuming in advance that it embodies a [7hh VNM-coherent] utility function.

An even more general term would be [decision_algorithm] which doesn't presume that the agent operates by [9h preferring outcomes].

7hh.title: Coherent decisions imply consistent utilities
7hh.clickbait: Why do we all use the 'expected utility' formalism?  Because any behavior that can't be viewed from that perspective, must be qualitatively self-defeating (in various mathy ways).

7s2.title: Moral uncertainty
7s2.clickbait: A meta-utility function in which the utility function as usually considered, takes on different values in different possible worlds, potentially distinguishable by evidence.

7t8.title: Meta-utility function
7t8.clickbait: Preference frameworks built out of simple utility functions, but where, e.g., the 'correct' utility function for a possible world depends on whether a button is pressed.

7t9.title: Attainable optimum
7t9.clickbait: The 'attainable optimum' of an agent's preferences is the best that agent can actually do given its finite intelligence and resources (as opposed to the global maximum of those preferences).

9h.title: Consequentialist cognition
9h.clickbait: The cognitive ability to foresee the consequences of actions, prefer some outcomes to others, and output actions leading to the preferred outcomes.
